The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | HDFC Bank net rises 31%
                                                                                                               HDFC Bank net rises 31%
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                           GOOD SHOW                                  
	Mumbai, July 14: HDFC Bank today beat analyst estimates by posting a 31 per cent rise in net profit for the first quarter ended June 30.         
	The countrys second largest private sector bank reported a profit of Rs 606.1 crore compared with Rs 464.35 crore in the corresponding period last year.         
	A strong growth fee income and treasury operations boosted the bottomline.         
	Other income jumped to Rs 1,043.85 crore (Rs 593.42 crore) and net interest income  earned from the banks core operations  rose to Rs 1,855.6 crore. The performance was driven by an average asset growth of 10.5 per cent and a net interest margin of 4.1 per cent.         
	For the quarter, the bank earned a total income of Rs 5,136.8 crore, an increase of Rs 921.6 crore over the corresponding quarter ended June 30, 2008.         
	HDFC Bank said the largest contributor to other income, which grew nearly 76 per cent, was fees and commissions (selling third party products like mutual funds and insurance) of Rs 649.3 crore, up 27 per cent over the corresponding quarter ended June 30, 2008.         
	Besides the commissions, the bank earned Rs 137.8 crore from foreign exchange and derivative transactions, and made a capital gain of Rs 256 crore on its investments.        
	HDFC Banks balance-sheet size increased by Rs 17,516.4 crore to Rs 186,115.0 crore on June 30. Total deposits were Rs 145,732 crore, up from Rs 130,918 crore on June 30, 2008.         
	Gross advances 2009 stood at Rs 105,288 crore, an year- on-year increase of 7.7 per cent.                                                                                                                                        
